value.json: {"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_2112": {}, "MG_P_2113": {}, "MG_P_2114": {}, "MG_P_2115": {}, "MG_P_2116": {}, "MG_P_2046": {}, "MG_P_2047": {}, "MG_P_2048": {}, "MG_P_2049": {}, "MG_P_2050": {}, "MG_P_2051": {}, "MG_P_2052": {}, "MG_P_2053": {}, "MG_P_2054": {}, "MG_P_2055": {}, "MG_P_2056": {}, "MG_P_2057": {}, "MG_P_2058": {}, "MG_P_2059": {}, "MG_P_2060": {}, "MG_P_2061": {}, "MG_P_2062": {}, "MG_P_2063": {}, "MG_P_2064": {}, "MG_P_2065": {}, "MG_P_2066": {}, "MG_P_2067": {}, "MG_P_2068": {}, "MG_P_2069": {}, "MG_P_2070": {}, "MG_P_2071": {}, "MG_P_2072": {}, "MG_P_2073": {}, "MG_P_2074": {}, "MG_P_2075": {}, "MG_P_2076": {}, "MG_P_2077": {}, "MG_P_2078": {}, "MG_P_2079": {}, "MG_P_2080": {}, "MG_P_2081": {}, "MG_P_2082": {}, "MG_P_2083": {}, "MG_P_2084": {}, "MG_P_2099": {}, "MG_P_2100": {}, "MG_P_2101": {}, "MG_P_2102": {}, "MG_P_2103": {}, "MG_P_2104": {}, "MG_P_2105": {}, "MG_P_2106": {}, "MG_P_2107": {}, "MG_P_2108": {}, "MG_P_2109": {}, "MG_P_2110": {}, "MG_P_2111": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "The lateral vestibular nucleus gives rise to the lateral vestibulo-spinal tract, the pathway that serves to adjust the postural musculature to changes in relation to gravity; it is under control of the \u201colder\u201d portions of the cerebellum.  Fibers also descend from the medial vestibular nucleus as the medial vestibulo-spinal tracts, these fibers are involved with postural adjustments to positional changes, using the axial musculature. The medial and inferior vestibular nuclei give rise to both ascending and descending fibers: the ascending fibers adjust the position of the eyes and coordinate eye movements of the two eyes by interconnecting the three cranial nerve nuclei involved in the control of eye movements\u2014CN III (oculomotor) in the upper midbrain, CN IV (trochlear) in the lower midbrain, and CN VI (abducens) in the lower pons.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_1964": {}, "MG_P_1965": {}, "MG_P_1966": {}, "MG_P_1967": {}, "MG_P_1968": {}, "MG_P_1969": {}, "MG_P_1970": {}, "MG_P_1971": {}, "MG_P_1972": {}, "MG_P_1973": {}, "MG_P_1974": {}, "MG_P_1975": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "The dentate nucleus is the major outflow from the cerebellum via the superior cerebellar peduncle. This peduncle connects the cerebellar efferents, through the midbrain, to the thalamus on their
way to the motor cortex. Some of the fibers terminate in the red nucleus of the midbrain, in
addition to those from the intermediate nucleus.
Most of the fibers, those from the dentate nucleus, terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of the thalamus. From here they are relayed to the motor cortex, predominantly area 4, and also the premotor cortex, area 6. The neocerebellum is
involved in motor coordination and planning.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_1940": {}, "MG_P_1941": {}, "MG_P_1942": {}, "MG_P_1943": {}, "MG_P_1944": {}, "MG_P_1945": {}, "MG_P_1946": {}, "MG_P_1947": {}, "MG_P_1948": {}, "MG_P_1949": {}, "MG_P_1950": {}, "MG_P_1951": {}, "MG_P_1952": {}, "MG_P_1953": {}, "MG_P_1954": {}, "MG_P_1955": {}, "MG_P_1956": {}, "MG_P_1957": {}, "MG_P_1958": {}, "MG_P_1959": {}, "MG_P_1960": {}, "MG_P_1961": {}, "MG_P_1962": {}, "MG_P_1963": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "The emboliform and globose, the intermediate nuclei, also project to brainstem nuclei, including the red nucleus of the midbrain. They also project to the appropriate limb areas of the motor cortex via the thalamus; these are the fibers involved in the comparator function of this part of the cerebellum, whereby the cerebellum adjusts the actual movement with the intended movement.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_1908": {}, "MG_P_1909": {}, "MG_P_1911": {}, "MG_P_1912": {}, "MG_P_1913": {}, "MG_P_1914": {}, "MG_P_1915": {}, "MG_P_1916": {}, "MG_P_1917": {}, "MG_P_1918": {}, "MG_P_1919": {}, "MG_P_1920": {}, "MG_P_1921": {}, "MG_P_1922": {}, "MG_P_1923": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "All (excitatory) afferents to the cerebellum go to both the
deep cerebellar nuclei (via collaterals) and the cerebellar
cortex. After processing in the cortex, the Purkinje neuron
sends its axon on to the neurons of the deep cerebellar
nuclei—all Purkinje neurons are inhibitory. Their
influence modulates the activity of the deep cerebellar
neurons, which are tonically active. The output of the deep cerebellar neurons, which is excitatory, influences neurons in the brainstem and cerebral cortex via the thalamus.
The connections of the cortical areas with the intracerebellar
nuclei follow the functional divisions of the cerebellum:
• The vestibulocerebellum is connected to the
fastigial nucleus, as well as to the lateral vestibular
nucleus;
• The spinocerebellum connects with the intermediate
nuclei (the globose and emboliform);
• The neocerebellum connects to the dentate
nucleus;
Axons from the deep nuclei neurons project from the
cerebellum to many areas of the central nervous system,
including brainstem motor nuclei (e.g., vestibular, reticular
formation) and thalamus (to motor cortex). In this way,
the cerebellum exerts its influence on motor performance.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_1895": {}, "MG_P_1896": {}, "MG_P_1897": {}, "MG_P_1898": {}, "MG_P_1907": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "All parts of the cerebral cortex contribute to the massive cortico-pontine system of fibers. These fibers descend via the anterior and posterior limbs of the internal capsule, then the inner and outer parts of the cerebral peduncle, and terminate in the pontine nuclei. The fibers synapse and cross and then project mainly to the neocerebellum via the  middle cerebellar peduncle. This input provides the cerebellum with the cortical information relevant\nto motor commands and the planned (intended) motor activities.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_2046": {}, "MG_P_2047": {}, "MG_P_2048": {}, "MG_P_2049": {}, "MG_P_2050": {}, "MG_P_2051": {}, "MG_P_2052": {}, "MG_P_2053": {}, "MG_P_2054": {}, "MG_P_2055": {}, "MG_P_2056": {}, "MG_P_2057": {}, "MG_P_2058": {}, "MG_P_2059": {}, "MG_P_2060": {}, "MG_P_2061": {}, "MG_P_2062": {}, "MG_P_2063": {}, "MG_P_2064": {}, "MG_P_2065": {}, "MG_P_2066": {}, "MG_P_2067": {}, "MG_P_2068": {}, "MG_P_2069": {}, "MG_P_2070": {}, "MG_P_2071": {}, "MG_P_2072": {}, "MG_P_2073": {}, "MG_P_2074": {}, "MG_P_2075": {}, "MG_P_2076": {}, "MG_P_2077": {}, "MG_P_2078": {}, "MG_P_2079": {}, "MG_P_2080": {}, "MG_P_2081": {}, "MG_P_2082": {}, "MG_P_2083": {}, "MG_P_2084": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "Direct pathway for involuntary control of movements. These pathways provide a link between the vestibular influences (i.e., gravity and balance) and the control of axial musculature, via the
spinal cord. The main function is to provide corrective  muscle activity when the body (and head) tilts or changes orientation in space.  The lateral vestibular nucleus, which is located in
the lower pontine region, gives rise to the lateral vestibulospinal
tract, that descends through the medulla and traverses
the entire spinal cord in the ventral white matter. It does not decussate. The fibers terminate in the medial portion of the anterior horn, namely, on those motor cells that control the axial musculature of the upper extremity. The medial vestibulo-spinal tract originates from the medial vestibular nucleus and also from the inferior vestibular nucleus.  These nuclei are involved in  connecting vestibular influences with head and eye movements and only projects to the upper cervical spinal cord.", "source": "medicine_graph"}

{"affects": {"nodes": {}, "pathways": {"MG_P_1925": {}, "MG_P_1926": {}, "MG_P_1927": {}, "MG_P_1928": {}, "MG_P_1929": {}, "MG_P_1930": {}, "MG_P_1931": {}, "MG_P_1932": {}, "MG_P_1933": {}, "MG_P_1934": {}, "MG_P_1935": {}, "MG_P_1936": {}, "MG_P_1937": {}, "MG_P_1938": {}, "MG_P_1939": {}}, "genes": {}}, "subevents": [], "description": "Efferents from the fastigial nuclei go to brainstem motor nuclei (e.g., vestibular nuclei and reticular formation), thus influencing balance and gait. They exit in a bundle that is found adjacent to the inferior cerebellar peduncle (named the juxtarestiform body).", "source": "medicine_graph"}

The parts of the basal ganglia that are involved with the modulation of movement are the putamen, the globus pallidus, both internal and external divisions, and as part of this system the subthalamic nucleus and the substantia nigra. ", "source": "medicine_graph"}
